[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, I can hear you right there.

165
00:15:16,022 --> 00:15:16,362
[SPEAKER_11]: Okay.

166
00:15:16,782 --> 00:15:19,204
[SPEAKER_11]: My son Wes is a bright, socially engaging,

167
00:15:19,938 --> 00:15:21,920
[SPEAKER_11]: 44-year-old college graduate.

168
00:15:22,320 --> 00:15:28,285
[SPEAKER_11]: He has cerebral palsy, which impacts his reflexes, mobility, and multitasking.

169
00:15:28,946 --> 00:15:30,988
[SPEAKER_11]: He gets easily fatigued.

170
00:15:31,608 --> 00:15:34,811
[SPEAKER_11]: Wes can't drive despite many years of specialized training.

171
00:15:35,872 --> 00:15:42,017
[SPEAKER_11]: He commutes an hour and a half to and then from work daily, often getting home at 9 or 10 p.m.

172
00:15:44,500 --> 00:15:49,001
[SPEAKER_11]: He makes an average of $17 an hour as a hospital transporter.

173
00:15:49,681 --> 00:15:53,363
[SPEAKER_11]: Wes does not want to be defined by his disability.

174
00:15:54,423 --> 00:16:02,285
[SPEAKER_11]: When Wes moved with us from out of state, we converted our lower level into a private studio apartment.

175
00:16:03,185 --> 00:16:12,428
[SPEAKER_11]: We began looking to section eight housing for disability and income status, a place of independence nearby, but not attached to his parents.

176
00:16:14,197 --> 00:16:21,321
[SPEAKER_11]: He eventually moved to a Medford Housing Authority apartment, where he lived for about five years until November of 2014.

177
00:16:21,381 --> 00:16:28,986
[SPEAKER_11]: The rent was based on income and was submitted each year for examination and determination.

178
00:16:30,046 --> 00:16:32,868
[SPEAKER_11]: He qualified under disability status.

179
00:16:33,668 --> 00:16:43,134
[SPEAKER_11]: It was a small one bedroom with a tiny living room, a very tiny kitchen that had no countertops, which made cooking very difficult.

180
00:16:43,768 --> 00:16:54,851
[SPEAKER_11]: The building was bug-ridden, but when management eventually called exterminators, drawers were dumped randomly, making a mess out of the preparation that Wes and I had done.

181
00:16:56,031 --> 00:16:58,792
[SPEAKER_11]: The carpeting was threadbare throughout.

182
00:16:59,372 --> 00:17:07,915
[SPEAKER_11]: There were also many smokers in the building, which led Wes to develop a smoker's cloth that continued for a couple of years after living there.

183
00:17:08,635 --> 00:17:12,076
[SPEAKER_11]: We worried about the clientele and their unregistered guests.

184
00:17:13,025 --> 00:17:15,366
[SPEAKER_11]: In general, the whole place was very depressing.

185
00:17:16,327 --> 00:17:20,368
[SPEAKER_11]: His parents, siblings, relatives, and Wes all felt uncomfortable.

186
00:17:21,909 --> 00:17:26,771
[SPEAKER_11]: Why were there not basic amenities and comfort provided in Section 8 housing?

187
00:17:28,112 --> 00:17:31,913
[SPEAKER_11]: Wes now lives in a two-bedroom condo in a converted school building.

188
00:17:33,054 --> 00:17:39,297
[SPEAKER_11]: Families, couples, and singles live in the 15 units, two of which are subsidized.

189
00:17:39,997 --> 00:17:42,138
[SPEAKER_11]: That means Wes pays half the taxes

190
00:17:42,791 --> 00:17:48,495
[SPEAKER_11]: half the condo fee, utilities, and half the price of this wonderful residence.

191
00:17:49,135 --> 00:17:53,538
[SPEAKER_11]: There's an occasional extra fee if a major upkeep project is needed.

192
00:17:54,599 --> 00:18:04,005
[SPEAKER_11]: West has two good-sized bedrooms, a decent kitchen, living room and dining room areas, a laundry room, plenty of closets, and communal outdoor space.

193
00:18:05,846 --> 00:18:07,667
[SPEAKER_11]: This unit was obtained through the state.

194
00:18:08,656 --> 00:18:14,081
[SPEAKER_11]: Applications are accepted based on low income need, low mortgage need.

195
00:18:14,941 --> 00:18:24,749
[SPEAKER_11]: We fronted Wes the down payment and he pays the monthly mortgage, which will be paid off in 12 years and other fees, taxes and utilities.

196
00:18:25,850 --> 00:18:37,520
[SPEAKER_11]: This transpired after I contacted Medgar City Hall and explained what we were looking for, including proximity to our home for our ongoing support and

197
00:18:38,927 --> 00:18:40,829
[SPEAKER_11]: A few months later, we were contacted.

198
00:18:41,689 --> 00:18:45,192
[SPEAKER_11]: My husband submitted the paperwork immediately, and Wes qualified.

199
00:18:46,413 --> 00:18:47,594
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm sorry, I'm getting teary.

200
00:18:48,154 --> 00:18:52,838
[SPEAKER_11]: We are all incredibly lucky, all feel incredibly lucky.

201
00:18:53,399 --> 00:18:55,060
[SPEAKER_11]: Wes feels a part of the community.

202
00:18:55,760 --> 00:19:04,908
[SPEAKER_11]: He often shovels out condo owners' driveways, get baked goods from a woman there, and watches football with a gentleman who has become a dear friend.

203
00:19:06,275 --> 00:19:15,597
[SPEAKER_11]: He feels like he's living in a clean safe place and has enough space to cook meals, have friends over and walk to her home without difficulty.

204
00:19:16,437 --> 00:19:23,019
[SPEAKER_11]: He feels respected and dignified in his residence, which spills out onto his outlook of life.

205
00:19:23,779 --> 00:19:25,780
[SPEAKER_11]: His friends and family love his place.

206
00:19:26,900 --> 00:19:27,620
[SPEAKER_11]: Life is good.

207
00:19:30,221 --> 00:19:30,861
[SPEAKER_11]: So that's it.

208
00:19:31,341 --> 00:19:35,182
[SPEAKER_11]: But what I wanna say is, I want that for more residents

